ive** (status = running) and exclude the current cron session:\\n\\n1. **cron:6f3323ef-607e-42a0-b946-611913081d31** — DTLX 5p Monitor — running — startedAt: 1776199558073 → running since ~20:44 UTC Apr 14, that's ~5h 57m ago... wait let me recalculate. \\n\\nLet me recalculate the duration more carefully using the current time of 02:44 UTC on April 15, 2026, checking the startedAt timestamp for this session. Now I'm calculating the elapsed time from the previous timestamp to the current one—that's about 2 hours and 9 minutes. Moving on to the next session, a Telegram group chat for the AHV DTLX ecosystem that started running around 02:40 UTC and has been active for approximately 4 minutes so far.\\n\\nThere's also a QLHV 5p monitor cron job that's been running for about 15 minutes, a Telegram direct message that's marked as done with no active duration, and a webchat session for the master orchestrator that's been inactive for about 19 minutes.\\n\\nI'm also seeing an orphaned cron job for sending messages to the Telegram group that's been running for roughly 13 hours, a cron job for the daily briefing that's marked as done, and a Telegram group for the AHV QLHV ecosystem.\\n\\nLooking at the rest of the sessions, there's a completed cron job from yesterday evening and another orphaned session from the Orbis QLHV report that's been sitting for about 15 hours.\\n\\nNow I'm checking the child sessions spawned by the DTLX ecosystem group. I can see there are three sessions still running—the prompt optimizer, one of the senior backend tasks, and the current session itself. Let me verify the exact status of that last one by looking at its most recent activity timestamp.\\n\\nLooking at the message context, this DTLX group session is actively building and polling processes, so it's definitely still running. I should compile the active master-orchestrator sessions into a report for the Lead.\\n\\nNow I'm filtering through all the master-orchestrator sessions to identify which ones are actually active and what they're doing, focusing on the cron jobs and Telegram sessions that have recent activity. Now I'm calculating the duration for each of the remaining sessions. The DTLX ecosystem group has been running for about 4 minutes, the QLHV monitor is at 15 minutes, and the orphaned cron job has been stale for roughly 13 hours. The daily briefing session from yesterday is still showing as completed, so I'll exclude that from the active report. Looking at the DTLX ecosystem, it has five active child sessions including the prompt-optimizer and multiple senior-backend agents that are actively running. The orphaned cron job has been sitting idle for over 13 hours, which is flagged as a concern. I'm now preparing to send this report directly to Lead through a session message.\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"text\",\n              \"text\": \"Now I'll compile the report and send to Lead.\\n\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"toolCall\",\n              \"id\": \"call_function_x2vobxwjjpom_1\",\n              \"name\": \"sessions_send\",\n              \"arguments\": {\n                \"sessionKey\": \"agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:direct:6053576134\",\n                \"message\": \"🌐 Orbis — Agent Status | 02:44 UTC 15 Apr\\n\\nActive sessions: 3\\n• cron:6f3323ef (DTLX 5p Monitor): running — 5-minute pipeline health check (DTLX ecosystem) — 6h 0m\\n• cron:ed2d0b5d (QLHV 5p Monitor): running — 5-minute pipeline health check (QLHV ecosystem) — 15m\\n• telegram:group:-5168104492 (DTLX Ecosystem Group): running — ⚡ACTIVE task — prompt-optimizer + 3×senior-backend + senior-frontend child sessions spawned — 4m\\n\\nIdle heartbeat sessions: 2\\n• telegram:direct:6053576134 (Lead poll): idle — awaiting next heartbeat — idle 19m\\n• telegram:group:-5163901258 (QLHV group): idle — last 5p report 02:11 UTC — idle 33m\\n\\nStale sessions: 1\\n• cron:ac986a8d: orphaned — ~13h stale (last active Ap